# EU Copyright Compliance Framework for AI Systems

## 1. Compliance System Establishment

### Continuous Lifecycle Management

- Implement copyright compliance checks as **mandatory guardrails** before any LLM invocation — not optional post-processing
- Maintain a documented copyright status for every ingested document in the system database
- Conduct regular audits of stored documents as rightsholders may update their opt-out declarations
- Integrate compliance checks into the document ingestion CI/CD pipeline — documents must never reach storage without passing copyright classification

### Documentation Requirements

- Record `copyright_status` (`clear`, `restricted`, `blocked`) per document in the database
- Store `copyright_reason` for all non-clear documents (the matched pattern and its legal basis)
- Maintain `guardrail_audit` logs per analysis run, including `processing_id`, classification results, and blocked documents
- Preserve the copyright assessment even after the document is deleted — audit trails are immutable

---

## 2. Copyright Risk Identification and Analysis

### Copyright Risk Levels

| Risk Level | Status | Trigger | Action |
|---|---|---|---|
| 🚫 BLOCKED | AI opt-out detected | DSM Art. 4(3) opt-out pattern found | HTTP 451, notify Admin, never pass to LLM |
| 🔴 HIGH | Database extraction | >50% of protected database extracted | Obtain license |
| 🟡 RESTRICTED | Reproduction restricted | "All Rights Reserved" or similar | Paraphrase only, factual extraction only |
| 🟢 CLEAR | No restrictions | Open license, public domain, or no protection | Cite source, proceed with processing |

### Known and Foreseeable Copyright Risks in AI Pipelines

- **Document ingestion**: Loading copyrighted PDFs/DOCX into storage constitutes reproduction (InfoSoc Art. 2)
- **Vector indexing**: Embedding copyrighted text in a RAG vector store is a persistent reproduction
- **LLM prompting**: Including copyrighted text in a prompt is a temporary reproduction (potentially Art. 5(1))
- **Output reproduction**: LLM output that quotes verbatim text from RESTRICTED docs violates Art. 2
- **Database extraction**: Extracting structured data from tariff/pricing databases may trigger the sui generis right (Database Directive Art. 7)
- **Fine-tuning**: Using opted-out documents in fine-tuning violates EU AI Act Art. 53(1)(c)

### Post-Deployment Risk Assessment

- Monitor for new opt-out declarations from rightsholders (e.g., publisher policy updates, AFNOR updates)
- Re-scan documents annually or when their source publisher/rightsholder is known to have updated their terms
- Track CJEU judgments on copyright + AI (evolving case law in 2025-2026)

